  "text": "The precise way anesthetics work remains mysterious. In this review, we focus upon anesthetic actions in the neuronal systems known to modulate sleep and arousal. An obvious parallel is that in both sleep and the anesthetic state there is a decreased response to external stimuli and a decreased level of consciousness. This raises the intriguing possibility that the hypnotic component of general anesthesia may arise via specific interactions in the brain with networks that regulate sleep and wakefulness [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . Our aim is to highlight important studies published in the past several years.",
